Metasoma
(Fig. 
1h
). Slightly longer than head plus mesosoma length (1.1
x
); in lateral view, 1.4 times longer than high. Second metasomal tergite short, reaching 1/3 if the metasoma; metasomal tergites 2 to 5 without punctures, subsequent tergites alutaceous. Hypopygium plough-shaped, shiny, smooth and large; prominent part of the ventral spine of the hypopygium very thin, 3.0 times longer than broad, with sparse white setae, apical setae short, not extending behind apex of the spine.

Only females are known (Fig. 
2g
). Galls appear in mid-April and larvae occupy the most part of the larval chamber (Fig. 
2c, e, f
). Adults emerge in early March of the following year.
